Date:  15/8/1918
Source:  Kia-ora Coo-ee
Author:
Vol / Page:  Second Series 2/5
Edition:  1981
Quote:  G.E.J.: Can any `Kia Ora Coo-ee-ite' dig up anything to beat this for the pure and unadulterated? A certain New Zealand Regiment, camped on the Jordan flats, recently came under the eagle eye of brother `Jacko', who immediately went `butcher's hook' or `ram's horn' and launched forth much frightfulness by lugging a 5.9 up on to one of the spare hills and chucking ironmongery promiscuously about the landscape.
Notes:

Date:  0/0/1966
Source:  English Language in Aust. & NZ, The
Author:  TURNER
Vol / Page:  177
Edition:
Quote:  <i>Much New Zealand colloquialism is shared with Australia, e.g. just quietly</i> `between you and me', <i>the strength of</i> `the essence of', <i>come a stumer</i> `be disappointed, come a cropper', or <i>go butcher's hook(s)</i>, rhyming slang for `go crook, display anger'
Notes:

Date:  0/0/1943
Source:  English as it is spoken in NZ
Author:  TURNER
Vol / Page:  90
Edition:
Quote:  <i>To go crook</i> is to show anger or annoyance, to `sling off at'; and <i>to go butcher's hook</i> is presumably a development of this rhyming slang.
Notes:
